{
  "text": "regulation of circulating insulin levels. Dietary fiber reduces insulin secretion by slowing the rate of nutrient absorption following a meal. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Experimentally, insulin sensitivity increases [CITATION_3] and body weight decreases [CITATION_4] on high-fiber diets. In addition, epidemiological analyses have suggested that fiber protects against hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and CVD. [14] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] The purpose of this study was to test the hypothesis that fiber consumption is independently and inversely associated with insulin levels, weight gain, and other CVD risk factors among adults, and to compare fiber with fat and other major dietary components.",
